5 related to such indebtedness. The board shall designate an
6 investment fiduciary for the reserve fund and adopt an investment
7 policy for the reserve fund consistent with subsection (5).
8 (7) (6) A board shall provide for the purchase of, the
9 contracting for, and the providing of supplies, materials,
10 services, insurance, utilities, third-party financing, equipment,
11 printing, and all other items as needed by the authority to
12 efficiently and effectively meet the needs of the authority using
13 competitive procurement methods to secure the best value for the
14 authority. The board shall make all discretionary decisions
15 concerning the solicitation, award, amendment, cancellation, and
16 appeal of authority contracts. A board shall provide for the
17 acquisition of professional services, including, but not limited
18 to, architectural services, engineering services, surveying
19 services, accounting services, services related to the issuance of
20 bonds, and legal services, in accordance with a competitive,
21 qualifications-based selection process and procedure for the type
22 of professional service required by the authority. An authority is
23 not required to use competitive bidding when acquiring proprietary
24 services, equipment, or information available from a single source,
25 such as a software license agreement. An authority may enter into a
26 cooperative purchasing agreement with the federal government, this
27 state, or other public entities for the purchase of goods or
28 services necessary for the authority. An authority may enter into
29 lease purchases or installment purchases for periods not exceeding
ERE H02802'25 (H-3) ys8z46

5
1 the anticipated useful life of the items purchased unless otherwise
2 prohibited by law. In all purchases made by the authority, all
3 other things being equal, preference shall must be given first to
4 products manufactured or services offered by firms based in the
5 authority's qualified metropolitan area, including, but not limited
6 to, the qualified city and each county in the qualified
7 metropolitan area, and next to firms based in this state, if
8 consistent with applicable law. The authority shall actively
9 solicit lists of potential bidders for authority contracts from
10 each qualified city and each county in the qualified metropolitan
11 area. Except as otherwise provided in this section, the authority
12 shall utilize competitive solicitation for all purchases authorized
13 under this act unless 1 or more of the following apply:
14 (a) Procurement of goods or services is necessary for the
15 imminent protection of public health or safety or to mitigate an
16 imminent threat to public health or safety, as determined by the
17 authority or its chief executive officer.
18 (b) Procurement of goods or services is for emergency repair
19 or construction caused by unforeseen circumstances when the repair
20 or construction is necessary to protect life or property.
21 (c) Procurement of goods or services is in response to a
22 declared state of emergency or state of disaster under the
23 emergency management act, 1976 PA 390, MCL 30.401 to 30.421.
24 (d) Procurement of goods or services is in response to a
25 declared state of emergency under 1945 PA 302, MCL 10.31 to 10.33.
26 (d) (e) Procurement of goods or services is in response to a
27 declared state of energy emergency under 1982 PA 191, MCL 10.81 to
28 10.89.
29 (e) (f) Procurement of goods or services is under a
ERE H02802'25 (H-3) ys8z46

