14 (a) The contract cost is less than $50,000.00.
15 (b) The contract is for emergency repair or construction
16 caused by unforeseen circumstances.
17 (c) The repair or construction is necessary to protect life or
18 property.
19 (d) The contract complies with requirements of applicable
20 state or federal law.
21 (9) (8) The board shall adopt a procurement policy consistent
22 with the requirements of this act and federal and state laws
23 relating to procurement. The procurement policy shall must include
24 a requirement for the authority to use its best efforts within the
25 competitive solicitation requirements of this section to achieve
26 fairness in the number and value of contracts for goods or services
27 entered into by the authority with firms based in the qualified
28 city and each county within the qualified metropolitan area,
29 consistent with applicable law. The board shall adopt a policy to
ERE H02802'25 (H-3) ys8z46

7
1 govern the control, supervision, management, and oversight of each
2 contract to which the authority is a party. The board shall adopt
3 procedures to monitor the performance of each contract including,
4 but not limited to, a contract that exists on the transfer date, to
5 assure execution of the contract within the budget and time periods
6 provided under the contract. The monitoring shall must include
7 oversight as to whether the contract is being performed in
8 compliance with the terms of the contract, this act, and federal
9 and state law procurement law. The chief executive officer or other
10 authorized employee of an authority shall not sign or execute a
11 contract until the contract is approved by the board. A board for
12 an authority shall establish policies to ensure that the authority
13 does not enter into a procurement or employment contract with a
14 person who has been convicted of a criminal offense incident to the
15 application for or performance of a contract or subcontract with a
16 governmental entity in this state. A board for an authority shall
17 establish policies to ensure that the authority does not enter into
18 a procurement or employment contract with a person who has been
19 convicted of a criminal offense, or held liable in a civil
20 proceeding, that negatively reflects on the person's business
21 integrity, based on a finding of embezzlement, theft, forgery,
22 bribery, falsification or destruction of records, receiving stolen
23 property, or violation of state or federal antitrust statutes, or
24 similar laws. The authority shall prepare an annual report to the
25 board, the qualified city, and each county within the qualified
26 metropolitan area detailing all contracts entered into by the
27 authority during the immediately preceding fiscal year. As used in
28 this subsection, if a person is a business entity, person includes
29 affiliates, subsidiaries, officers, directors, managerial
